Singapore Stocks: Dyna-Mac, Golden Agri, Hyflux, Keppel Corp.

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-03-03T10:04:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-02/darco-water-keppel-singapore-air-singapore-stocks-preview.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
increased 0.3 percent to 3,037.35 at the close. Almost three
stocks rose for each that fell in the benchmark index of 30
companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 13.9 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Palm-oil producers: Crude palm-oil futures for May delivery
gained as much as 1.6 in  Kuala Lumpur  today, extending its
advance to a third day.    Golden Agri-Resources Ltd. (GGR)  , the world’s second-
biggest palm-oil producer, climbed 2.2 percent to 70 Singapore
cents.  Indofood Agri Resources Ltd. (IFAR)  , the palm-oil unit
of  Indonesia ’s biggest noodle maker, gained 0.4 percent to
S$2.36.  Wilmar International Ltd. (WIL)  , the world’s largest
palm-oil trader, advanced 1.8 percent to S$5.16.    Hi-P International Ltd. (HIP)  , the electronics
manufacturing services provider whose clients include Apple Inc.
and BlackBerry-maker Research in Motion Ltd., climbed 1.7
percent to S$1.22. Apple’s introduction of a new version of the
iPad should benefit Hi-P because it’s been supplying a
“mechanical component” for the tablet computer, Tan Ai Teng,
an analyst at DBS Group Holdings Ltd., wrote in a note to
clients today.    Hyflux Ltd. (HYF)  , the Singapore company that has
desalination projects in Algeria and  Libya , advanced 2.8 percent
to S$1.86. The company said it will increase focus on  Asia  as
its projects in Libya face delays amid mounting political unrest
in the North African nation. Separately, the company said it is
exploring the possibility of issuing preference shares to help
fund investments in Asia.  Keppel Corp. (KEP SP), the world’s biggest builder of oil
rigs, increased 0.9 percent to S$11.60. The company said a unit
bought a 27.8 percent stake in Dyna-Mac Holdings Ltd. (DMHL SP),
a provider of engineering services to the oil and gas industry,
for S$87.5 million. Dyna-Mac surged 17 percent to 44 Singapore
cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
